**Previous Frame Conditioning.** To ensure consistency for the whole video reconstruction, we use an autoregressive way to reconstruct the video, by conditioning the model on the last frame \(^{N}\) of the previously estimated video clip \(}\). We concatenate the previous frame with the latent representation \(}\) on the temporal dimension as a condition to obtain \(}=[z_{0}^{0},_{t}]^{(N+1) C^{}  H^{} W^{}}\). Due to the absence of the previous frame in the first video clip, we randomly drop the previous frame condition by applying Gaussian noise to the frame latent representation. During inference, the first video clip is reconstructed directly from the events and text data without the previous frame. For subsequent video clips, the reconstruction process utilizes the last frame from the previous video clip as a condition to ensure temporal coherency and smoothness.

